to the editor a president is entitled to tilt the judiciary any way he wants says senator mitch mcconnell news article june 27 i am not sure that the men who drafted the constitution would agree they did not give the president exclusive control over the appointment of judges precisely because as one of them said at the constitutional convention granting such power would cause the people to think we are leaning too much towards monarchy indeed that the executive had too great an influence over the judiciary was one of the complaints against george iii set forth in the declaration of independence the power of appointing federal judges is therefore shared between the president and the senate for as james madison said the latter body will afford security against any incautious or corrupt nomination by the executive mark kozlowski new york june 28 2001 the writer is staff attorney brennan center for justice new york university school of law

